### FIELD CLASSIFICATION

Anchor on stable fields. Never anchor on volatile fields — they fire once and never match again.

| Stable (anchor on these) | Volatile (never anchor on these) |
|--------------------------|----------------------------------|
| Rule / detection name | Timestamps, event time |
| Process name | PID, parent PID, TID |
| Process path / directory | Session GUID, correlation ID, event ID |
| File name | Ephemeral source ports |
| Signed publisher / signer | Full command line w/ embedded variable paths or args |
| Parent process name | Per-run temp filenames (random suffixes) |
| Detection source / tool | Dynamic DHCP-assigned internal IPs |
| Stable command-line substring | Auto-incrementing counters |

A valid filter needs at least one high-specificity stable anchor (path, file name, signer, or rule name) PLUS at least one qualifier (scope, parent process, or behavioral field). Never ship a single-field blanket filter; never ship an over-constrained one-shot.

---

### OPERATOR SELECTION

| Operator | Use when |
|----------|----------|
| EQUALS | Value is exact and invariant (rule name, file name, full process name, signer) |
| STARTSWITH | Path that may gain a version/build suffix (`C:\Program Files\Tool\` survives `\v2.3\bin\`) |
| ENDSWITH | Stable trailing token (extension, fixed binary name at a variable path) |
| CONTAINS | Stable substring inside a longer variable string (cmdline flag, argument token) |
| MATCHES (regex) | Only when a single static pattern captures benign variation a fixed operator can't; keep it tight |

Default to the least permissive operator that still survives benign variation. Avoid EQUALS on any path containing a version number — use STARTSWITH on the version-independent prefix.

---

### SCOPE DETERMINATION

| Scope | Apply when |
|-------|------------|
| Environment-wide | FP pattern is identical across the fleet (e.g., a signed tool deployed everywhere, a platform behavior) |
| Host-scoped `[SCOPED]` | FP is specific to one asset (lab box, scanner host, single dev machine) |
| User-scoped `[SCOPED]` | FP is tied to one account's legitimate workflow (admin, service account) |

Choose the narrowest scope that still covers the full FP pattern. If the benign activity is genuinely fleet-wide, do not artificially scope to host/user — that just leaves the same FP firing elsewhere.

---

### FP/TP BOUNDARY PRESERVATION

The anchor set must preserve whatever distinguishes this FP from a true positive. Identify what a TP would look like and ensure the filter would NOT catch it:

- Benign = signed binary in a known path → anchor on path + signer, so an unsigned copy or a copy from a different path still alerts.
- Benign = specific scanner IP doing the scanning → anchor on source IP + rule, so the same rule from any other source still alerts.
- Benign = known parent chain → anchor on parent process, so the same child spawned by a different parent still alerts.

State the preserved boundary explicitly in the supporting documentation.

---

### IP HANDLING IN FILTERS

- Filter match values use clean IPs — no defang brackets. A filter matches the real value.
- Private / local IPs are weak anchors (often dynamic, always internal). Do NOT anchor solely on them. If used, pair with a stable qualifier. Ranges: RFC 1918 (`10/8`, `172.16/12`, `192.168/16`), `127/8`, `169.254/16`, `100.64/10`, multicast/reserved, and IPv6 `::1`, `fc00::/7`, `fe80::/10`.

